04974nam a22006255i 9780822383673DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161867  a97808223836737 a10.1515/97808223836732doi  a(DE-B1597)553898  a(OCoLC)1226678834  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.89/9152211 aPovinelli, Elizabeth A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cunning of Recognition :bIndigenous Alterities and the Making of Australian Multiculturalism /cElizabeth A. Povinelli; ed. by George Steinmetz, Fatma Müge Göcek, Nancy Rose Hunt, Webb Keane, Julia Adams. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b7 b&w photos, 9 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics, History, and Culture : 3000tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Critical Common Sense -- t1 / Mutant Messages -- t2 / The Vulva Thieves (Atna Nylkna): Modal Ethics and the Colonial Archive -- t3 / Sex Rites, Civil Rights -- t4 / Shamed States -- t5 / The Poetics of Ghosts: Social Reproduction in the Archive of the Nation -- t6 / The Truest Belief Is Compulsion -- tNotes -- tSelected Works Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Cunning of Recognition is an exploration of liberal multiculturalism from the perspective of Australian indigenous social life. Elizabeth A. Povinelli argues that the multicultural legacy of colonialism perpetuates unequal systems of power, not by demanding that colonized subjects identify with their colonizers but by demanding that they identify with an impossible standard of authentic traditional culture.Povinelli draws on seventeen years of ethnographic research among northwest coast indigenous people and her own experience participating in land claims, as well as on public records, legal debates, and anthropological archives to examine how multicultural forms of recognition work to reinforce liberal regimes rather than to open them up to a true cultural democracy. The Cunning of Recognition argues that the inequity of liberal forms of multiculturalism arises not from its weak ethical commitment to difference but from its strongest vision of a new national cohesion. In the end, Australia is revealed as an exemplary site for studying the social effects of the liberal multicultural imaginary: much earlier than the United States and in response to very different geopolitical conditions, Australian nationalism renounced the ideal of a unitary European tradition and embraced cultural and social diversity.While addressing larger theoretical debates in critical anthropology, political theory, cultural studies, and liberal theory, The Cunning of Recognition demonstrates that the impact of the globalization of liberal forms of government can only be truly understood by examining its concrete—and not just philosophical—effects on the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAboriginal AustraliansxClaims. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxEthnic identity. 0aMulticulturalismzAustralia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Julia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGöcek, Fatma Müge, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHunt, Nancy Rose, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeane, Webb, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSteinmetz, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/